    <h1>Houston is an underrated food city.</h1>
    </p>
    <p>I grew up and spent the first 18 years of my life in Houston. It was only after I moved out that I started to appreciate the city's diversity. We've got everything from a bustling Chinatown to some of the best Texas BBQ, incredible Vietnamese food, Steakhouses, Ramen, Tex-Mex, you name it. I might not be a local anymore, but I like to think I know a thing or two about the city's food scene. There's something for everyone here, so I've broken my list of recommendations into different categories. </p>

    <h1>Tex-Mex / Mexican</h1>
    <p>This seems as good a place to start as any. Houston Tex-Mex restaurants are known mostly for their fajita platters, which usually feature skirt steaks marinaded in a lime-salsa-cumin-etc deliciousness mixture. Compared to traditional Mexican cuisine, Tex-Mex generally features a buttload of cheese - queso, for example, is a big thing here and can often be ordered as an appetizer. </p>
    <p>Besides that, most of the emphasis is on the aforementioned marinaded steaks and the absurdly large portion sizes. Everything is bigger in Texas, including our waistlines.
    </p>
